summary.seg: This manuscript contains a collection of Works by Athanasius, archbishop of Alexandria (295-373). It was copied around the middle of the 16th century in Italy by the scribe Michael and another contemporary hand. Owned by Silvius Elwes (ca. 1576-1638), chaplain of Trinity College, the codex was donated by him to the College Library.

support.material:
Western paper, folded in folio. Watermarks: pp. 1-16, 33-361 Anchor in a circle surmounted by a six-point star, with countermark TC surmounted by a clover ( 68 40 ) in the centre of the leaf, identical to Sosower Ancre 96, which is dated to c. 1550-1552 (Rome).
pp. 17-32, 362-419 Justice with countermark BS surmounted by a clover ( 117 c. 53 ) in the centre of the leaf, identical to Sosower Justice 2, which is dated to 1556 (Rome).
pp. 420-730, f. [iii] Anchor in a circle surmounted by a six-point star, with countermark B E ( c. 67 c. 43 ) , very similar to Sosower Ancre 49, which is dated to c. 1553.

Western paper. Watermarks: f. [ii] Pitcher with two handles, surmouted by a crescent, with letters difficult to decipher ( 60 ca. 25 ) in the upper part of the leaf, no precise matches in the principal repertoires.
f. [iv] Name G NEWTON 1810 ( 60 38 ) in the centre of the leaf, datable to 1810, and comparable (but without date) to Gravell Watermark Archive, Names/Words WORD.229.1 , which is dated to 1802.

supportDesc.foliation: Two endleaves at the beginning and at the end of the manuscript are unnumbered (ff. [i]-[ii], [iii]-[iv]). The manuscript has been paginated in black/grey ink, in Arabic numerals, in the upper margin right (on the recto of the leaves) and left (on the verso), from 1 to 730. The pagination skips the numbers 99 and 289, and from 389 goes directly to 400; moreover various numbers are repeated (the errors in the ink pagination were corrected in pencil): 226a and 226b, 458a, and 458b, 459a and 459b, 462a and 462b, 463a and 463b, 464a and 464b, 573a and 573b, 574a and 574b, 643a and 643b, 644a and 644b, 673a and 673b, 674a and 674b. The leaves are numbered as follows: ff. [i]-[ii] + pp. 1-98, 100-225, 226a, 226b, 227-288, 290-389, 400-457, 458a, 458b, 459a, 459b, 460-461, 462a, 462b, 463a, 463b, 464a, 464b, 465-572, 573a, 573b, 574a, 574b, 575-642, 643a, 643b, 644a, 644b, 645-672, 673a, 673b, 674a, 674b, 675-730 + ff. [iii]-[iv]

collation.p: The manuscript consists of quaternions alternating with ternions (generally three quaternions followed by a ternion etc.). At the beginning there are two later endleaves (ff. [i]-[ii]), one is at the end of the manuscript (f. [iii]).

list.item: Quire 496-1 pp. 723-730, f. [iii] ( the 6th leaf is missing, without loss of text)

collation.catchwords: Vertical catchwords on the last verso, lower part, written from the top down. They are not always visible due to the position near the gutter.
collation.signatures:
Some Greek signatures, by Hand A (Michael, see Hand description), are visible in the upper margin, external corner, of the first recto of the quires; the majority of them are lost due to trimming:
α΄ (1)-β΄ (2) on pp. 1 and 17
δ΄ (4) on p. 49
ιε΄ (15) on p. 214. Hand A, moreover, traced little crosses in the centre of the upper margin of the first recto of the quires (see e.g. pp. 49, 122, 229).

supportDesc.condition: The manuscript is in good condition. A large part of f. [ii] is lost and was restored with paper. Some stains of blue ink are visible on the upper and external edges of the leaves, see e.g. pp. 61 and 494.

handNote.p: pp. 1-486, 505-524, 529-532, 711-730 Hand A: the majority of the text has been written by Michael (16th century) Michael (16th century) (Μιχαήλ, RGK III, 475), a scribe active in Venice (the hand, in my opinion, cannot be identified with the one of Emmanuel Bembaines, as it was assumed in consequence of a communication by F.C. Burkitt in Canart (1963), p. 60).
The text is written in a very light brown ink; titles and initials, as well as some marginal notes, in red, now very faded.
The scribe wrote a few annotations in the margins.
pp. 487-504, 525-528, 533-710 Hand B: the remaining texts have been written by a contemporary hand, in a minuscule script which has some forms and characteristics in common with Michael's.
The text is written in brown ink; titles and initials in red.
Hand a: passim there are a few additions by another hand, rather hesitant, see e.g. p. 175, where this scribe made an addition to the title, and p. 277, in the upper margin.
Hand b: another hand added two titles, on p. 483 and p. 494.

decoDesc.decoNote:
Friezes in red ink are present at the beginning of some of the texts:
p. 1: rope motif
pp. 63, 131, 175, 203: simple undulating linear frieze with clover leaves at both ends
pp. 277, 377: small undulated linear friezes.
Initials with decoration in a branch motif (see e.g. p. 1).
The texts often end in a cul-de-lampe disposition. The lines are in certain cases followed by three points in red ink (see e.g. p. 62) .

additions.p: A later hand added a table of contents to the manuscript in Latin on f. [ii] recto.
On pp. 277-537 there are not rubrics. A later hand added titles on p. 483 and p. 494.
On p. 1, in the upper and external margin, there are some annotations: B.9.8 (present shelfmark) and, erased with a line, C 4 27 .
On the left pastedown the present shelfmark has been written in red pencil.

binding.p: 16th/17th century western full leather binding, pasteboards. Golden tooling on both covers: arms of Silvius Elwes (see History) in an oval, on its two sides initials S. E.. The arms exhibit traces of color, red and blue. Gold tooling on the boards' edges. Edges are coloured in blue/green. On the spine, gold tooling with title Athanasii opera; in the upper, central and lower part are pasted three paper labels with the shelfmark. 345 250 80

origin.p: The manuscript was copied by the scribe Michael, who was active in Italy, and another contemporary hand, around the middle of the 16th century.

history.provenance: The codex was owned by Silvius Elwes (ca. 1576-1638) Silvius Elwes (ca. 1576-1638) , Chaplain of Trinity College.
history.acquisition: It was donated by Silvius Elwes to the Trinity College Library between 1626 and 1630 (see P. Gaskell, Trinity College Library: the first 150 years (Cambridge, 1980), p. 234). On the lower part of p. 1 is pasted the Trinity College bookplate. On pp. 1 and 730 there are stamps of Trinity College Library.

recordHist.source: Description (2020) partly draws on M.R. James, The Western Manuscripts in the Library of Trinity College Cambridge (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1900), vol. 1, pp. 270-271.
